Rating: 4
This is a very nice cake. I have a few problems with the way the method is layed out, and have adjusted it so: 1. When buttering the pan, the butter should be the consistency of cold cream; do not use melted butter. 2. Make sure that you allow the cooked apples to cool before you arrange them in the bottom of the prepared pan, otherwise the heat from the apples will melt the butter/sugar coating. 3. Do not boil the syrup until you have arranged the apples in the pan. 4. As with most cakes, make sure the eggs are at room temperature. 5. Begin whipping the eggs BEFORE adding the sugar. You want the eggs to provide a bit of rise to the cake, and whipping them first, then slowly adding the sugar as they whip will ensure a better mix. Then add the vanilla and Calvados. 6. Make sure the melted butter is cool before adding it to the cake mixture. Of course, as with all recipes, it is important to read through the directions at least twice before beginning. Doing so, in this recipe, will tell you that the apples are not cooked in 1.75 cups of sugar! I've made this cake five times using the method I decribe above and it has turned out perfectly each time.

